#: ../../../reference/generated/numpy.atan.rst:4
msgid "numpy.atan"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:2
msgid "Trigonometric inverse tangent, element-wise."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:4
msgid "The inverse of tan, so that if ``y = tan(x)`` then ``x = arctan(y)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:0
msgid "Parameters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:9
msgid "**x**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:-1
msgid "array_like"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:15 numpy.arctan:42
msgid "**out**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:-1
msgid "ndarray, None, or tuple of ndarray and None, optional"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:12
msgid ""
"A location into which the result is stored. If provided, it must have a "
"shape that the inputs broadcast to. If not provided or None, a freshly-"
"allocated array is returned. A tuple (possible only as a keyword argument) "
"must have length equal to the number of outputs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:23
msgid "**where**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:-1
msgid "array_like, optional"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:18
msgid ""
"This condition is broadcast over the input. At locations where the condition "
"is True, the `out` array will be set to the ufunc result. Elsewhere, the "
"`out` array will retain its original value. Note that if an uninitialized "
"`out` array is created via the default ``out=None``, locations within it "
"where the condition is False will remain uninitialized."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:29
msgid "**\\*\\*kwargs**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:26
msgid ""
"For other keyword-only arguments, see the :ref:`ufunc docs <ufuncs.kwargs>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:0
msgid "Returns"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:-1
msgid "ndarray or scalar"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:34
msgid ""
"Out has the same shape as `x`.  Its real part is in ``[-pi/2, pi/2]`` "
"(``arctan(+/-inf)`` returns ``+/-pi/2``). This is a scalar if `x` is a "
"scalar."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:47
msgid ":obj:`arctan2`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:48
msgid ""
"The \"four quadrant\" arctan of the angle formed by (`x`, `y`) and the "
"positive `x`-axis."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:49
msgid ":obj:`angle`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:50
msgid "Argument of complex values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:54
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:55
msgid ""
"`arctan` is a multi-valued function: for each `x` there are infinitely many "
"numbers `z` such that tan(`z`) = `x`.  The convention is to return the angle "
"`z` whose real part lies in [-pi/2, pi/2]."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:59
msgid ""
"For real-valued input data types, `arctan` always returns real output. For "
"each value that cannot be expressed as a real number or infinity, it yields "
"``nan`` and sets the `invalid` floating point error flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:63
msgid ""
"For complex-valued input, `arctan` is a complex analytic function that has "
"[``1j, infj``] and [``-1j, -infj``] as branch cuts, and is continuous from "
"the left on the former and from the right on the latter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:67
msgid "The inverse tangent is also known as `atan` or tan^{-1}."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:70
msgid "References"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.arctan:71
msgid ""
"Abramowitz, M. and Stegun, I. A., *Handbook of Mathematical Functions*, 10th "
"printing, New York: Dover, 1964, pp. 79. https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cbm/"
"aands/page_79.htm"
msgstr ""

